fields.name: Nose
fields.description: The human nose is the primary entryway of the respiratory system, consisting of the external nostrils, nasal cavity, and nasal vestibule, lined with mucosa containing ciliated epithelium and mucus-producing glands. Its anatomical structures create diverse microenvironments that support microbial colonization.

fields.name: Lungs
fields.description: The lungs are paired organs of the lower respiratory tract responsible for gas exchange, composed of bronchi, bronchioles, and alveoli lined with epithelial cells and mucus. The lungs are now known to harbor a low-biomass microbiome, which contributes to immune regulation and the maintenance of respiratory health.

fields.name: Skin
fields.description: The skin is the largest organ of the body, serving as a physical and immunological barrier that protects against environmental insults, pathogens, and water loss. It is composed of the epidermis, dermis, and subcutaneous tissue, each providing distinct microenvironments.

fields.name: Oral cavity
fields.description: The oral cavity is the entry point of the digestive system, consisting of structures such as the lips, tongue, teeth, gums, palate, and salivary glands. It provides a complex and heterogeneous environment that supports a rich microbiome.

fields.name: Gut
fields.description: The gut is a major component of the digestive system, extending from the stomach to the intestines, and is responsible for nutrient absorption, digestion, and immune regulation.

fields.name: Streptococcus pneumoniae
fields.age_range: Neonates (0–1 year): occasional colonization. Infants and children (1–12 years): high colonization rates in the nasopharynx; primary age group for otitis media and other respiratory infections. Adolescents (13–18 years): moderate colonization. fields.description: Streptococcus pneumoniae – Gram-positive, encapsulated, alpha-hemolytic bacterium; a common commensal of the human nasopharynx; opportunistic pathogen responsible for respiratory infections such as pneumonia, otitis media, and sinusitis, as well as invasive diseases like bacteremia and meningitis; capable of producing a polysaccharide capsule, which is a major virulence factor, and exhibits variable antibiotic resistance.

fields.name: Streptococcus mitis
fields.age_range: Neonates (0–1 year): occasional colonization, mostly in hospital or oral environments. Infants and children (1–12 years): moderate colonization, primarily in the oral cavity. Adolescents (13–18 years): persistent colonization. Adults (≥18 years): widespread colonization.
fields.description: Streptococcus mitis – Gram-positive, alpha-hemolytic bacterium; a common commensal of the oral cavity and upper respiratory tract; generally non-pathogenic but can act as an opportunistic pathogen causing endocarditis or bacteremia in vulnerable patients; closely related to other viridans group streptococci and capable of horizontal gene transfer, including antibiotic resistance genes.

fields.name: Streptococcus salivarius
fields.age_range: Neonates (0–1 year): occasional early colonization, in the oral cavity after birth. Infants and children (1–12 years): moderate to high colonization Adolescents (13–18 years): persistent colonization in the oral cavity and pharynx. Adults (≥18 years): widespread colonization.
fields.description: Streptococcus salivarius – Gram-positive, alpha-hemolytic bacterium; a prominent commensal of the oral cavity and upper respiratory tract; generally non-pathogenic and considered beneficial for oral health by inhibiting pathogenic bacteria; occasionally implicated in opportunistic infections such as bacteremia in immunocompromised patients.

fields.name: Streptococcus parasanguinis
fields.age_range: Neonates (0–1 year): rare colonization. Infants and children (1–12 years): moderate colonization Adolescents (13–18 years): persistent colonization Adults (≥18 years): widespread colonization in the mouth and upper respiratory tract.
fields.description: Streptococcus parasanguinis – Gram-positive, alpha-hemolytic bacterium; a commensal of the oral cavity and upper respiratory tract; plays a role in early dental plaque formation and maintenance of oral microbiota; generally non-pathogenic but can be involved in opportunistic infections such as endocarditis in vulnerable patients.

fields.name: Streptococcus anginosus
fields.age_range: Neonates (0–1 year): occasional colonization. Infants and children (1–12 years): moderate colonization. Adolescents (13–18 years): persistent colonization. Adults (≥18 years): widespread colonization.
fields.description: Streptococcus anginosus – Gram-positive, facultatively anaerobic bacterium; member of the Streptococcus anginosus group (SAG); a commensal of the oral cavity, gastrointestinal, and urogenital tracts; capable of forming abscesses and causing opportunistic infections including bacteremia, endocarditis, and deep tissue abscesses; exhibits biofilm formation and can contribute to polymicrobial infections.

fields.name: Finegoldia magna
fields.age_range: Neonates (0–1 year): rare colonization. Infants and children (1–12 years): low to moderate colonization. Adolescents (13–18 years): persistent but low-level presence. Adults (≥18 years): widespread colonization
fields.description: Finegoldia magna – Gram-positive, anaerobic, coccoid bacterium; a common commensal of human skin and mucosal surfaces but also a significant opportunistic pathogen; associated with soft tissue infections, wound infections, abscesses, and device-related infections; known for strong virulence factors, including biofilm formation, protein L production, and immune evasion mechanisms.

fields.name: Streptococcus australis
fields.age_range: Neonates (0–1 year): rare early colonization, usually through exposure to caregivers. Infants and children (1–12 years): moderate colonization. Adolescents (13–18 years): persistent colonization. Adults (≥18 years): widespread colonization in the oral cavity
fields.description: Streptococcus australis – Gram-positive, alpha-hemolytic bacterium; a member of the viridans group streptococci and a commensal of the oral cavity; also occasionally present in the nasal cavity as part of the upper respiratory tract microbiota; typically non-pathogenic but may contribute to dental biofilm formation; rarely associated with opportunistic infections such as bacteremia or endocarditis in immunocompromised individuals.

fields.name: Streptococcus constellatus
fields.age_range: Neonates (0–1 year): rare colonization, mostly acquired from maternal sources Infants and children (1–12 years): moderate colonization in upper respiratory tract. Adolescents (13–18 years): persistent colonization Adults (≥18 years): widespread colonization in the oral cavity, throat.
fields.description: Streptococcus constellatus – Gram-positive, facultatively anaerobic bacterium; part of the Streptococcus anginosus group (SAG), known for its strong association with abscess formation; typically a commensal of the oral cavity, respiratory tract, and gastrointestinal tract but can act as an opportunistic pathogen causing deep-seated infections, including lung abscesses, empyema, brain abscesses, and bacteremia; often found in polymicrobial infections.

fields.name: Streptococcus dysgalactiae
fields.age_range: Neonates (0–1 year): rare colonization; occasional infections. Infants and children (1–12 years): moderate colonization of the throat and skin Adolescents (13–18 years): persistent colonization of the upper respiratory tract Adults (≥18 years): widespread presence.
fields.description: Streptococcus dysgalactiae – Gram-positive, β-hemolytic bacterium belonging to Groups C and G streptococci; commonly colonizes the skin and upper respiratory tract; capable of causing infections similar to Streptococcus pyogenes, including pharyngitis, cellulitis, soft tissue infections, and bacteremia; also associated with more severe invasive disease in vulnerable individuals; exhibits virulence factors such as M-protein variants and the ability to invade tissues.

fields.name: Streptococcus infantis
fields.age_range: Neonates (0–1 year): occasional early colonization Infants and children (1–12 years): moderate colonization Adolescents (13–18 years): persistent colonization, usually asymptomatic. Adults (≥18 years): widespread colonization in the mouth and upper respiratory tract
fields.description: Streptococcus infantis – Gram-positive, alpha-hemolytic bacterium; a member of the Streptococcus mitis group and a common commensal of the oral cavity and pharynx; typically non-pathogenic but may participate in dental biofilm formation; occasionally associated with opportunistic infections such as bacteremia or endocarditis, particularly in individuals with weakened immunity or following invasive dental procedures.

fields.name: Streptococcus sanguinis

fields.description: Streptococcus sanguinis – Gram-positive, alpha-hemolytic bacterium; a member of the viridans group streptococci and a commensal of the oral cavity; also occasionally present in the nasal cavity as part of the upper respiratory tract microbiota; plays an important role in early dental biofilm formation and oral microbiome balance; rarely associated with opportunistic infections such as endocarditis or bacteremia, especially following invasive dental procedures.

fields.name: Streptococcus intermedius
fields.age_range: Neonates (0–1 year): rare colonization. Infants and children (1–12 years): moderate colonization Adolescents (13–18 years): persistent colonization; usually asymptomatic. Adults (≥18 years): widespread colonization.
fields.description: Streptococcus intermedius – Gram-positive, facultatively anaerobic bacterium; member of the Streptococcus anginosus group (SAG); a commensal of the oral cavity, upper respiratory tract, and gastrointestinal tract; strongly associated with abscess formation, including brain, liver, and lung abscesses; can cause opportunistic infections such as bacteremia and endocarditis; often involved in polymicrobial infections.

fields.description: Staphylococcus cohnii – Gram-positive, coagulase-negative bacterium; a skin commensal and occasional nasal colonizer; generally non-pathogenic but can act as an opportunistic pathogen in immunocompromised or hospitalized patients; associated with device-related infections, bloodstream infections, and biofilm formation; may exhibit variable antibiotic resistance.

fields.description: Staphylococcus simulans – Gram-positive, coagulase-negative bacterium; a skin commensal and occasional nasal colonizer in humans; generally non-pathogenic but can act as an opportunistic pathogen, particularly in hospitalized or immunocompromised individuals; associated with device-related infections, wound infections, and bloodstream infections; capable of biofilm formation and may exhibit variable antibiotic resistance.

fields.description: Staphylococcus saprophyticus – Gram-positive, coagulase-negative bacterium; a commensal of the urogenital tract and skin; a common cause of urinary tract infections (UTIs), particularly in young sexually active women; generally non-pathogenic in other body sites but can act as an opportunistic pathogen; capable of biofilm formation and exhibits variable antibiotic resistance.
